<DOC><DOCNO> AP880308-0305 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-03-08-88 1518EST</FILEID><FIRST>u f PM-WallStreet3pm     03-08 0495</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Wall Street 3pm,0516</SECOND><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Stocks rose broadly today in heavy trading,strengthened by dividend-related buying strategies, takeoverspeculation and a desire by institutional money managers to improvefirst-quarter portfolio performances.   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks rose 20.72 pointsto 2,077.09 by 3 p.m. EST.   Among broader market barometers, the New York Stock Exchange'scomposite index measuring alllisted issues rose 1.22 to 151.75. TheAmerican Stock Exchange's market value index rose 1.91 to 296.05.   Wall Street analysts said the market's strength was a good signthat partly reflected a move by investment managers to put unusedmoney to work before the end of the first quarter March 31.   ``The one thing institutions want to avoid is lack ofperformance at end of a quarter,'' said Philip C. Puccio, managerof institutional trading at Dillon Read andamp; Co. in New York.   Others said speculators who had sold stock on the hunch themarket would decline were aggressively buying, a phenomenon knownas short-covering which can boost prices dramatically.   Activity in stocks subject to takeover speculation also helpedstrengthen prices. Still, there was an underlying feeling that WallStreet remains deeply affected by the uncertain aftermath of theOctober crash.   ``We're still in that bear market mentality,'' said HankStreifler, senior vice president on the trading floor at ShearsonLehman Hutton Inc. ``We haven't moved over that hump.''   Gaining issues outnumbered losers by more than 2-to-1 on theNYSE, with 1,111 up, 447 down and 409 unchanged. Volume on the BigBoard totaled 207.81 million shares with an hour of trading left.   About one-fourth of the volume today came from trading in stocksthat carry dividend yields of at least 9 percent: Chemical NewYork, Detroit Edison, Pacific Gas andamp; Electric and McDermottInternational.   Investors who buy Detroit Edison's stock before Thursday willcapture the right to receive the next quarterly dividend payment.The deadline to capture the dividend in the other three issuesexpires today.   Among notable blue-chip stocks, IBM rose { to 117}, GeneralElectric rose 1{ to 44~ and Philip Morris rose 1 to 93].   Reebok rose 1 tp 17} in heavy trading, a sign of takeoverspeculation. The company said it knew of no reason for theactivity. Salomon rose { to 24\ after indications that RevlonChairman Ronald Perelman, who has expressed interest in Salomon,would make a major acquisition soon.   Several oil stocks also rose on takeover speculation, based onthe theory that Mobil expects $1.2 billion from the sale of itsMontgomery Ward retailing unit and Pennzoil will soon get $3billion from its settlement with Texaco. Mobil and Pennzoilconceivably could use the money for acquisitions.   Unocal rose 2] to 38] in heavy trading, Phillips Petroleum rose{ to 15] and Kerr-McGee rose ~ to 36}.   Metals stocks were broadly higher, reflecting rising commodityprices. Alcoa rose 1{ to 47}, Asarco rose } to 24} and Phelps Dodgerose 1\ to 41}.</TEXT></DOC>